Tor (The Onion Router)
ğŸ’¡ Definition:

Tor is a network designed for anonymity.
It routes your internet traffic through multiple encrypted layers (like an onion), making it nearly impossible to trace your identity or location.

ğŸ”§ How it works:

You connect to Tor Browser.

Your traffic passes through 3 random nodes (servers):

Entry node â†’ knows your IP.

Relay node â†’ only passes encrypted data.

Exit node â†’ connects to the final website.

Each layer decrypts one part of the data, so no single node knows both the sender and receiver.

ğŸ§© Example Scenario:

A journalist in a country with strict censorship uses Tor to:

Access blocked news websites.

Communicate anonymously with sources.

Avoid government tracking.

âœ… Advantages:

Strong anonymity.

Free and open-source.

Bypasses censorship.

âŒ Disadvantages:

Slow (because of multi-layer encryption).

Some exit nodes may be monitored.

Accessing illegal dark web content through Tor can lead to serious legal consequences.

ğŸ§  Security Insight:

Tor is often used by:

Whistleblowers and activists (for privacy)

Researchers (to explore dark web safely)

Cybercriminals (for illegal markets â€” which we must never engage in)

